o exploration of non-text media including an analysis of Michael Jackson’s pop videos. Arranged chronologically, the book establishes links between texts and periods and examines how conjunctions of ‘queer’, ‘gay’, and ‘lesbian’ can be related to, and are challenged by, a Gothic tradition. All of the chapters were specially commissioned for the collection, and the contributors are drawn from the forefront of academic work in both Gothic and Queer Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre), EnglishxHistory and criticism. 0aHomosexuality in literature. 4aGothic 2017. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / LGBT Studies / Gay Studies.2bisacsh  aA Passage to India.  aFrankenstein.  aGhosts.  aGothic romances.  aMary Shelley.  aMichael Jackson.  aTeleny.  aThriller.  agay sexuality.  alesbian Gothic horror.  amiscegenation.  aqueer Gothic.  aracial monstrosity.1 aBruhm, Steven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHughes, William, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMahawatte, Royce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMason, Diane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalmer, Paulina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRigby, Mair, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmith, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aThomas, Ardel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTownshend, Dale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWisker, Gina, econtributo